'''''Louis Riel''''' is a 2003 historical biography in [[comics]] by Canadian cartoonist [[Chester Brown]].  It deals with [[M<U+00E9>tis people (Canada)|M<U+00E9>tis]] rebel leader [[Louis Riel]]'s antagonistic relationship with the newly established [[Canadian Confederation|Canadian government]].  It begins shortly before the 1869 [[Red River Rebellion]], and ends with Riel's 1885 hanging for [[Treason Act 1351|high treason]].  The book explores the possibly schizophrenic aspect of Riel's personality<U+2014>he believed God had named him Prophet of the New World, destined to lead the M<U+00E9>tis people to freedom.

The work is noted for its emotional disengagement, its intentionally flat dialogue, and a minimalist drawing style inspired by [[Harold Gray]]'s comic strip ''[[Little Orphan Annie]]''.  Unusual in comics of the time, it includes a full scholarly apparatus: a foreword, index, bibliography and end notes.  The appendix provides insight on Brown's creative process and biases, highlighting where he changed historical facts to create a more engaging story, such as incorporating a conspiracy theory not widely accepted by historians.  Brown became interested in the issue of property rights while researching the book, which led to a very public change in his politics from [[anarchism]] to [[libertarianism]].

Although Brown intended it to be published in book form only, ''Louis Riel'' was initially serialized in ten issues between 1999 and 2003.  It was the first comic book to receive a grant from the [[Canada Council|Canada Council for the Arts]].  It was critically well received, winning three [[Harvey Award]]s.  The serialization sold poorly, but the book version was a surprise bestseller, and its success played a major part in gaining shelf space for serious [[graphic novel]]s in mainstream North American bookstores.

==Overview==
Subtitled "A Comic-Strip Biography",{{sfn|MacDonald|2012|p=56}} ''Louis Riel'' looks at [[M<U+00E9>tis people (Canada)|M<U+00E9>tis]] rebel leader [[Louis Riel]], detailing his leadership in the [[Red River Rebellion|Red River]] and [[North-West Rebellion|North-West]] rebellions.  It does not attempt a complete retelling of Riel's life, omitting long periods and ignoring many aspects of his personality.  Instead the focus is on his "antagonistic relationship with the [[Government of Canada|Canadian government]]"{{sfn|Hutcheon|2010|p=47}} from 1869 to 1885.{{sfn|Booker|2010|p=370}}  The story comprises 241 pages of the 271-page book, and is fleshed out with a complete [[Critical apparatus|scholarly apparatus]]: a foreword, bibliography, [[index (publishing)|index]], map section and extensive end notes.{{sfnm|1a1=Hutcheon|1y=2010|1p=47|2a1=Marshall|2y=2005|3a1=MacDonald|3y=2012|3pp=57<U+2013>58}}  It has strong [[Historiography|historiographical]] elements, detailing in the appendix the research done and choices made by the author in developing a story.{{sfn|MacDonald|2012|pp=57<U+2013>58}}

Brown grew up in [[Quebec]], where the majority speaks French, and where Riel is often considered a martyr.  However Brown, who grew up speaking only English,{{sfn|Weisblott|2008}} was largely ignorant of Riel's story{{Sfn|Sim|2003|loc=part 1}} until he read [[Maggie Siggins]]' 1994 biography ''Louis Riel: A Life of Revolution''.{{sfnm|1a1=Hajdu|1y=2009/2010|2a1=Epp|2y=2002}}  Many of Brown's favourite topics are entwined in ''Louis Riel'': [[anti-authoritarianism]], outsider religion, [[insanity]], and accuracy and objectivity in nonfiction.{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}}  A central incident in the book is an eight-panel sequence in which Riel has a revelatory experience on a hilltop in Washington, D.C.  He experiences visions and talks to God, who declares him Prophet of the New World and instructs him to lead his people to freedom.  On the cover of the book, however, we see Riel standing alone in the wilderness, staring into the sky, leaving open the question of whether what he witnessed was real.{{sfn|Wolk|2007|p=155}}

==Background==
{{Quote box
|quote  = "I read [''Louis Riel: A Life of Revolution''] and thought, 'That's a good dramatic story<U+2014>it'd make a good strip.'"
|source = Chester Brown, interview with [[Dave Sim]] (2003){{sfnm|1a1=Sim|1y=2003|1loc=part 1|2a1=Hajdu|2y=2009/2010}}
|width = 25em}}
In 1995, Brown published the [[anti-psychiatry]] comics essay "[[The Little Man (comics)#My Mom was a Schizophrenic|My Mom was a Schizophrenic]]".  The six-page strip came with two pages of end notes gathered from his research.  Brown enjoyed this project and thought he would like to take on another project in which he could "cram a lot of research into a comic strip".{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=164}}  When he came across Siggins' biography of Riel, he had been working on the experimental ''[[Underwater (comics)|Underwater]]'' series, a project on which felt he had lost his way.{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=162}}  His father died in late 1997, and he decided he did not "want to waste [his] time with projects that weren't working out".{{sfn|Tousley|2005}}  In 1998, he turned his attention to Riel,{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=164}} putting the unpopular ''Underwater'' series on hold.{{sfn|Arnold|2004-06-28}}

While researching, Brown came across two books by [[Tom Flanagan (political scientist)|Tom Flanagan]]: ''Louis "David" Riel: "Prophet of the New World"'' (1996) and ''Louis Riel and the Rebellion: 1885 Reconsidered'' (2000).  Brown found ''"Prophet of the New World"'' particularly intriguing as it dealt with Riel's religious ideas while reevaluating his alleged diagnosis of mental illness,{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=164}} two topics Brown had especial interest in, having previously made "eccentric" [[Chester Brown's Gospel adaptations|adaptations of the Gospel]], and comics dealing with his mother's [[schizophrenia]].{{sfn|Wolk|2004}}  He also came across books by researcher Don McLean and historian Douglas N. Sprague that advanced the [[conspiracy theory]] that the 1885 North-West Rebellion was deliberately provoked by Prime Minister [[John A. Macdonald]] to gain support for the building of the [[Canadian Pacific Railway#Building the railway, 1881<U+2013>1885|transcontinental railway]].{{sfn|Bell|2006|pp=164<U+2013>165}}

Brown had already gained a reputation for improvised storytelling by the time he began work on ''Louis Riel''.  With ''Underwater'', he had intended to write a script, but in the end decided to improvise.  The results were unsatisfactory, and Brown decided to write a full script beforehand for his next project.  The script for ''Louis Riel'' came to over 200 pages.{{sfnm|1a1=Epp|1y=2002|2a1=Wivel|2y=2011b}}

Brown's was not the first depiction of the M<U+00E9>tis leader in comics.  [[James Simpkins]], a Canadian cartoonist best known for Jasper the Bear, made a mildly anti-Riel two-page strip in 1967,{{sfn|Brown|May 2002|p=25}} and Pierre Dupuis produced a French-language two-page summary in 1979.{{sfn|Brown|October 2002|p=24}}  A 23-page pro-Riel strip appeared in ''Canadian History Comic Book No. 2: Rebellion'' in 1972.{{sfn|Brown|February 2003|p=24}}  In 1980, the Italian [[Hugo Pratt]] created a character called [[Jesuit Joe]] who was supposed to have descended from Riel.{{sfn|Paquin|2006|p=8}}  Publishing house Les <U+00C9>ditions des Plaines published two books on Riel: Robert Freynet's 58-page ''Louis Riel en bande dessin<U+00E9>e'' in 1990,{{sfn|Brown|October 2002|p=24}} and Zoran and Toufik's ''Louis Riel, le p<U+00E8>re du Manitoba'' in 1996, both in French.{{sfnm|1a1=Brown|1y=May 2002|1p=25|2a1=Paquin|2y=2006|2p=8}}  Riel also played a secondary role in the 1995 [[Comics album|album]] ''Le cr<U+00E9>puscule des Bois-Br<U+00FB>l<U+00E9>s''.{{sfnm|1a1=Paquin|1y=2006|1p=8|2a1=Brown|2y=February 2003|2p=26}}

==Plot==
<!--

     PLEASE KEEP IN MIND that this is a summary of events as they happened in Brown's book

-->[[File:Canada provinces 1870-1871.png|right|thumb|alt=Map of Canada, 1870<U+2013>1871|Canada in 1870, after [[Manitoba]] (square in lower centre) was [[Manitoba Act|admitted]] into Confederation following the [[Red River Rebellion]] ]]
The government of the [[Canadian Confederation|new Dominion of Canada]] (established 1867), under Prime Minister John A. Macdonald, has made a deal with the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] to purchase [[Rupert's Land]]<U+2014>vast tracts of land in northern North America.  The French-speaking M<U+00E9>tis<U+2014>people who are half [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Native]], half [[White people|white]], and inhabit parts of Rupert's Land<U+2014>dispute that their land can be sold to the Canadians without their consent.  In the [[Red River Colony|Red River settlement]], the M<U+00E9>tis, led by Louis Riel, dodge political manoeuverings on the part of Lieutenant Governor [[William McDougall (politician)|William McDougall]] and some of the English-speaking settlers, while seizing [[Fort Garry]].  After an armed standoff at English-speaking settler [[John Christian Schultz|John Schultz]]'s home, the M<U+00E9>tis declare a provisional government and vote Riel their president, with an even number of French and English representatives.{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}}  Schultz escapes from prison and rounds up a number of men with the intention of freeing the prisoners from Fort Garry, but when Riel lets the prisoners go, Schultz's men return for home.  On the way, a number of them pass Fort Garry, where they are captured and imprisoned.  One of the prisoners, Thomas Scott, relentlessly quarrels with the guards, showering them with racial epithets.  Eventually, the provisional government convicts him of treason and executes him by firing squad.  The remaining prisoners are released, and the provisional government enters into negotiations with Ottawa, resulting in the founding of the province of [[Manitoba]].  They are unable to get an [[amnesty]] for the execution of Scott, however.  The Canadian army arrives, ostensibly to keep the peace.  Riel flees to the U.S., and the anglophone population assumes governance.{{sfn|Wivel|2011a}}

Schultz takes control of Manitoba, and the government of [[Ontario]] offers a cash reward for Riel's capture, dead or alive.  Macdonald secretly sends Riel money to disappear, as his death would lose him votes in Quebec but allowing him to live would cost him votes in English Canada.  Riel flees from town to town in the U.S. as [[bounty hunter]]s try to track him down.{{sfn|Marshall|2005}}  In 1873, he returns to the Manitoba and wins a seat in the federal [[Parliament of Canada|Parliament]] in a by-election. He fears actually sitting in parliament because there is still a bounty on his head, and continues to live in hiding.{{sfn|Marshall|2005}}  In 1874, he wins his seat again.{{sfn|Wivel|2011a}}  Schultz wins a seat in the settlement as well, however, and [[Alexander Mackenzie]] has become Prime Minister, running on promises not to grant the rebels an amnesty.  Riel is expelled from Parliament for failing to sit, but wins his seat again in the next by-election.  The frustrated government finally extends an amnesty to the rebels<U+2014>all except Riel, whose amnesty is conditional on a five-year banishment from Canada.  During his exile, he has a [[Vision (spirituality)|visionary experience]] on a hilltop in Washington, D.C., in which God names him David, the Prophet of the New World,{{sfn|Wivel|2011a}} and tells him to lead the M<U+00E9>tis to freedom.{{sfnm|1a1=Arnold|1y=2003-05-30|2a1=Wolk|2y=2007|2p=155}}  In 1876, Riel is secretly committed by a friend to a lunatic asylum near Montr<U+00E9>al under a false name.{{sfn|Wolk|2007|p=153}}

[[File:Battle of Batoche Print by Seargent Grundy.jpg|thumb|left||alt=Print of the Battle of Batoche|Contemporary print of the [[Battle of Batoche]], on which Brown based the cover to ''Louis Riel'' #8 ]]
Over the next several years, the M<U+00E9>tis, unhappy with the Canadian government's handling of their land rights, move farther west across the [[Canadian Prairies|Prairies]].{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}}  There as well, they see their petitions to the government repeatedly ignored and their rights trampled on.  Finally, after being ignored for too long, the M<U+00E9>tis search for Riel in [[Montana]], hoping his return will force the Canadians to take their claims seriously.  He is reluctant at first, having started a family and settled down as a schoolmaster.  In the hopes of getting money from the Canadian government for his tenure administering the Red River settlement (by this time known as [[Winnipeg]]), he moves his family to [[Batoche, Saskatchewan|Batoche]] (now in [[Saskatchewan]]) in mid-1884.  Macdonald has returned to the prime ministership and conspires with [[George Stephen, 1st Baron Mount Stephen|George Stephen]], president of the financially-burdened [[Canadian Pacific Railway]], to use the situation to gain support for finishing the railway.  By inciting a violent revolt amongst the M<U+00E9>tis, the government can justify funding the railway to move troops to the Prairies.{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}}  The M<U+00E9>tis under Riel respond with arms as intended, after Riel breaks from the Catholic Church, declaring "Rome has fallen!" and breathing the [[Holy Spirit]] into his followers, thereafter known as the [[Exovedate]].  Tensions build until the bloodshed at the [[Battle of Duck Lake]], where the Riel and his followers drive back the [[North-West Mounted Police]].  Macdonald takes this as a cue to send two thousand troops to the area.  At the [[Battle of Fish Creek]], the outnumbered M<U+00E9>tis manage to drive back the Canadians, but at the [[Battle of Batoche]], while Riel is increasingly immersed in religious activities, the M<U+00E9>tis finally suffer defeat.  In the hope that his trial will provide an opportunity to get the M<U+00E9>tis' story to the public, Riel surrenders instead of fleeing.{{sfnm|1a1=Marshall|1y=2005|2a1=Wivel|2y=2011a}}

In July 1885, Riel is put on trial in Regina for his role as leader in the North-West Rebellion.{{sfn|Lander|2005|p=117}}  Against his will, Riel's lawyer tries unsuccessfully to defend him on grounds of insanity.{{sfn|Wivel|2011a}}  He is found guilty of [[Treason Act 1351|high treason]], and, though the jury pleads for mercy, sentenced to hang.  In response to the pleas of Quebeckers to pardon Riel, Macdonald responds, "He shall hang though every dog in Quebec bark in his favour".{{sfn|Hajdu|2009/2010}}  After reconciling himself with the Church, Riel is hanged in Regina on 16&nbsp;November 1885.{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}}  In the aftermath, the remaining rebels receive a pardon, Macdonald and Stephen continue in their success, and Riel's wife dies.{{sfn|Marshall|2005}}

==Primary characters==
{{multiple image
| width    = 100
| footer   = Photographs of the book's two adversaries
| image1   = Louis Riel.jpg
| alt1     = Louis Riel
| caption1 = [[Louis Riel]]
| image2   = John A Macdonald (ca. 1875).jpg
| alt2     = John A. Macdonald
| caption2 = [[John A. Macdonald]]
}}

===Louis Riel===
Riel (1844<U+2013>85) was a French-speaking M<U+00E9>tis politician from a devoutly Catholic background.{{sfn|Stanley|1963|pp=13<U+2013>20}}  He founded and named the Province of Manitoba (a [[Cree language|Cree]] word meaning "the god that speaks"{{sfn|Epp|2002}}{{efn|Other translations contradict the one given here (see [[Manitoba]]), but "the god that speaks" is the translation Riel's character gives in the story.}}).  He led the two M<U+00E9>tis rebellions against the Canadian government: the Red River Rebellion of 1869<U+2013>70 and the North-West Rebellion of 1885.  Following the latter, he was hanged for high treason.{{sfn|Johnson|2012b}} Riel remains an ambiguous and controversial figure in [[History of Canada|Canadian history]], and Brown's depiction maintains that ambiguity.{{sfn|Hajdu|2009/2010}}

Riel is depicted as charismatic, Montr<U+00E9>al-educated, and speaks English, making him a natural leader to the M<U+00E9>tis,{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}} though his leadership is flawed<U+2014>he ignores the military advice of his peers in battle, placing his faith in God that the M<U+00E9>tis will defeat the Canadians.{{sfn|Shulgan|2003}}  He is depicted as having a [[Messiah complex|messianic complex]] and possibly having schizophrenia.{{sfn|Wolk|2007|p=153}}  He is unsure of himself, averse to bloodshed, and easily convinced to flee to the U.S. to avoid capture.{{sfn|Marshall|2005}}

===John A. Macdonald===
Macdonald (1815<U+2013>91) was the first [[Prime Minister of Canada]], in office 1867<U+2013>73, and again 1878<U+2013>91.{{sfn|Johnson|2012a}}  Brown depicts the Prime Minister in the role of scheming villain and [[caricature]]s his features in an absurd manner, giving him an extremely oversized nose{{sfnm|1a1=Arnold|1y=2003-05-30|2a1=Shulgan|2y=2003}} and showing him as a drunk.  He is a man of ambitions and will not let anyone stand in the way of his legacy.  In his notes, however, Brown discloses that he does not see Macdonald as the villain he has portrayed in the book.{{sfn|Hajdu|2009/2010}}  Brown's distrust of [[big government]] leads him to push the conspiracy theory side of the story to Macdonald's detriment, but, in the end, he states that he "would rather have lived in a state run by John A. Macdonald than one run by Louis Riel".{{sfnm|1a1=Bell|1y=2006|1p=166|2a1=Park|2y=2011}}

==Style==
''Louis Riel'' is noted for its emotional restraint,{{sfnm|1a1=Hutcheon|1y=2010|1p=47|2a1=Wolk|2y=2007|2p=154}} and intentionally flat and expository dialogue.{{sfn|Wolk|2007|p=154}}  The book makes frequent deliberate use of silent panels, focused on imagery{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=165}} with the narrative moved forward by the characters' actions.  Riel's "despairs over the decisions he makes" are expressed through pictures, as Brown had come to believe that historical comics had been too "narration-heavy".{{sfn|Hutcheon|2010|p=46}}  He wanted ''Louis Riel'' "to show what the medium is capable of",{{sfn|Hutcheon|2010|p=46}} and made use of greater panel-to-panel continuity.{{sfn|Hutcheon|2010|p=47}}  While the grid of panels gives a feeling of page symmetry, the pages are not composed as a unit<U+2014>scenes change anywhere on the page with little regard to page layout.{{sfn|Wivel|2011a}}

Printed on yellowish paper,{{sfnm|1a1=Booker|1y=2010|1p=370|2a1=Hajdu|2y=2009/2010}} each page conforms strictly to a rhythmic six-panel grid,{{sfnm|1a1=Hutcheon|1y=2010|1p=47|2a1=Booker|2y=2010|2p=370|3a1=Wolk|3y=2004|4a1=Wivel|4y=2011a}} in contrast to the free placement of panels that characterized Brown's [[Chester Brown's autobiographical comics|autobiographical period]].{{sfn|Paquin|2006|p=9}}  Tone and mood are set by the composition of the panels, as during Riel's trial when all tonal variation is dropped, and the white figures are placed against a heavy black background,{{sfn|Hajdu|2009/2010}} emphasizing the claustrophobic atmosphere.{{sfn|Marshall|2005}}

The language barriers that separate the characters are made visual by Brown's having all francophone characters drop the letter "h" in their dialogue (e.g. "over t'e last several days&nbsp;..."), and by putting "translated" French-language dialogue in <U+27E8>[[Bracket#Angle brackets or chevrons <U+27E8> <U+27E9>|chevron brackets]]<U+27E9>, and [[Cree language]] dialogue in <U+27E8><U+27E8>double-chevrons<U+27E9><U+27E9>.  Riel, who was an educated and sophisticated speaker of French, is shown to struggle with English.  These touches emphasize that English was not yet a dominant language in the regions in which the story unfolds.{{sfn|Marshall|2005}}  Brown's semantics in his [[speech balloon]]s are consistent and deftly handled.  The size and weight of the dialogue in the speech balloons is varied according to speech patterns, and sound effects are varied according to how close they are to the reader.{{sfn|Wivel|2011a}}

{{Quote box
|quote  = "My&nbsp;... one goal was to make the artwork look as much as the artwork in ''[[Little Orphan Annie]]'' as possible, I was trying to draw like [[Harold Gray]]"
|source = Chester Brown, interview with Matthias Wivel (2004){{sfn|Wivel|2011b}}
|width = 25em}}
Brown's drawing style had always changed from project to project.{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}}  He frequently cited [[Harold Gray]] of ''[[Little Orphan Annie]]'' as the primary influence on the drawing style of ''Louis Riel''<U+2014>restrained artwork which avoids extreme closeups,{{sfn|Heer|2003}} and blank-eyed characters with large bodies, small heads, and oversized noses.{{sfnm|1a1=Booker|1y=2010|1p=370|2a1=Arnold|2y=2003-05-30|3a1Wolk|3y=2007|3p=153}}  Gray's drawing and compositional style was well suited to the subject of ''Louis Riel''.  Gray often used his strip as a public platform for politics, and ''Louis Riel'' was also very public and outward-looking.  This approach is in great contrast to the inward-looking comics Brown had previously been known for<U+2014>notably his autobiographical work.  His [[Hatching|cross-hatching]] style was reminiscent of the editorial cartoonists of Riel's time.  Gray's outdoor scenes were inspired by the Illinois plains of Gray's youth, terrain similar to that of Manitoba and Saskatchewan.{{sfn|Spurgeon|2009}}

Brown also acknowledges significant debts to [[Jaxon|Jack Jackson]]'s historical comics,{{sfn|Rogers|2011|loc=part 8}} [[Herg<U+00E9>]]'s ''[[Adventures of Tintin|Tintin]]'',{{sfn|Lander|2005|p=119}} and the extremely exaggerated style of [[Larry Gonick]]'s ''[[The Cartoon History of the Universe|Cartoon History of the Universe]]''.{{sfn|Wivel|2011b}}  He says he referred to [[Jack Hamm]]'s ''How to Draw Animals'' when drawing the horses that appear frequently throughout the book,{{sfn|Sim|2003|loc=part 3}} which were rendered running with their legs splayed, as an artist may have depicted them in the days before the influence of [[Eadweard Muybridge]]'s photographs of bodies in motion.{{sfn|Wivel|2011a}}  Brown drew each of the 1325{{sfn|Paquin|2006|p=8}} panels separately on watercolour paper{{sfn|Tousley|2005}} on a block of wood he placed on his lap in lieu of a [[Drawing board|drawing table]],{{sfn|Shulgan|2003}} which allowed him seamlessly to rearrange, insert, and delete panels as he saw fit.{{sfn|Wivel|2011b}}  The drawings were [[Inker|finished]] using both a thin [[ink brush]] (no larger than size 0) and [[dip pen]] with a [[Speedball (art products)|Hunt]] 102 [[nib (pen)|nib]] and black ink.<ref name="TorontoPublicLibrary" />

==Use of appendices==
[[File:Thomas Bland Strange.jpg|thumb|140px|alt=Photograph of [[Thomas Bland Strange]]|[[Thomas Bland Strange]]'s appearance is ahistorical, but his name amused Brown.]]
When he began ''Louis Riel'', Brown had increasingly been making use of notes and appendices in his work,{{sfn|Park|2011}} beginning with his researching and annotating the 1994 comics essay, "My Mom was a Schizophrenic".{{sfnm|1a1=Bell|1y=2006|1p=164|2a1=Park|2y=2011}}  He added appendices to the 1998 collection of short strips, ''[[The Little Man (comics)|The Little Man]]'', and the 2002 reprinting of ''[[I Never Liked You]]''.{{sfn|Park|2011}}  In ''Louis Riel'', the appendix totalled 23 pages, along with a bibliography and an index.{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=166}}  [[Alan Moore]]'s use of extensive end notes in his and [[Eddie Campbell]]'s ''[[From Hell]]'', another fictional reconstruction of a historical event, influenced Brown's appendices.{{sfn|Epp|2002}}  In the comics essay "Dance of the Gull Catchers" which closes the ''From Hell'' appendices, Moore metaphorical reveals to the reader the myriad choices he could have made from the available historical evidence when putting together his version of the [[Jack the Ripper]] story.{{sfn|MacDonald|2012|p=58}}

Allowing him to "tell the best story and tell the truth",{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}} Brown's notes were self-reflexive, drawing attention to the artistic choices he made when putting together the book.{{sfnm|1a1=Hutcheon|1y=2010|1p=47|2a1=Bell|2y=2006|2p=166}}  Brown makes explicit the inaccuracies in the book,{{sfnm|1a1=Hutcheon|1y=2010|1p=47|2a1=Wolk|2y=2007|2p=155}} as when he realized his drawings of William McDougall did not match up with descriptions of him by biographers as a "portly" and "heavily built man".{{sfn|Hutcheon|2010|p=47}}  Brown chose not to redraw McDougall's scenes, deciding he "could live with that level of inaccuracy".{{sfnm|1a1=Hutcheon|1y=2010|1p=47|2a1=MacDonald|2y=2012|p=58}}  He also admits that he deliberately changed some of the historical details, as when he has Prime Minister Macdonald in talks with the Hudson's Bay Company in London<U+2014>Macdonald was not in London at that time and did not directly participate in the negotiations.  In other instances, Brown noted where he paid special care to historical details: the dialogue of [[Trial of Louis Riel|Riel's trial]] comes directly from court transcripts.{{sfn|Hutcheon|2010|p=48}}  Brown makes clear in his notes the amount of research undertaken for the book, emphasizing both its authenticity and his desire to show the different aspects of Riel's ambiguous story.{{sfn|Hajdu|2009/2010}}  Many of his changes were made for space considerations, as he intended the book to be limited to about two hundred pages.{{sfn|Wivel|2011b}}

The notes have a self-deprecatory tone that is common in North American comics, tracing its roots to the awkwardly self-aware [[underground comix]] of the 1960s and 1970s.  They also reveal Brown's process in shaping the story from conflicting sources.{{sfn|Lander|2005|p=119}}  He acknowledges some of the more capricious details.  He explains he was not committed to the conspiracy theory he presented, but included it in order to present Macdonald in a certain light: "[V]illains are fun in a story", he said, and he was "trying to tell this tale in an engaging manner".{{sfn|Park|2011}}  He also included a "Major-General [[Thomas Bland Strange]]" in an 1885 meeting at which the general was not actually present.  Brown explains that he included Strange because he was amused by the Major-General's name.{{sfn|Park|2011}}

==Publication history==
[[File:Kobo ereader touch black front.JPG|right|thumb|alt=Photograph of Kobo e-reader|Brown's ''Louis Riel'' and ''[[Paying for It]]'' were the first two [[Drawn and Quarterly]] comics to become available for e-readers, in a non-exclusive deal with [[Kobo Inc.]] ]]
''Louis Riel'' was originally meant by Brown to be published in book form, but was convinced by his publisher, Chris Oliveros, to serialize it first.{{sfnm|1a1=Bell|1y=2006|1p=165|2a1=MacDonald|2y=2004}}  [[Drawn and Quarterly]] published the ten comic-book instalments from 1999 until 2003.{{sfn|Booker|2010|p=369}}  Brown was granted [[Canadian dollar|CAD]] $6000 by the [[Canada Council|Canadian Council for the Arts]] in 2001 to assist in its completion.{{sfn|Weisblott|2008}}<ref name="CanadaCouncil2001Grants" />  The full volume was published in hardcover in 2003 and softcover in 2006.{{sfn|Booker|2010|p=370}}  The book sold out its first printing in two months,{{sfn|Arnold|2004-04-12}} went through multiple printings, and had sold fifty thousand copies by the beginning of 2011.{{sfn|Adams|2011}}  The original serialization sold poorly, making the book's success a surprise.{{sfn|McGillis|2011}}

The comic book and the collection both came with an extensive appendix, and the collection came with a bibliography and an index, all of which were tightly hand-lettered by Brown.{{sfnm|1a1=Shulgan|1y=2003|2a1=Park|2y=2011|3a1=Wolk|3y=2004}}

In the original serialization, as the series progressed and the influence of Harold Gray became stronger, the characters' heads became smaller while their bodies and hands grew larger, with Riel appearing "like the [[Hulk (comics)|Hulk]] in a wool suit" after his hilltop religious revelation.{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}}  Brown redrew many of the earlier drawings to make them consistent with the later ones in the collected edition,{{sfn|Tousley|2005}} adding backgrounds and redrawing many of the panels.{{sfn|Shulgan|2003}}

In 2012, Drawn and Quarterly first began offering comics in [[e-book]] format, prompted in part by Brown.  His ''Louis Riel'' and ''[[Paying for It]]'' were the first two books made available,{{sfnm|1a1=Reid|1y=2011|2a1=Indian Country Today|2y=2012}} though Brown is a print-lover who professes little interest in e-books, or computers in general.{{sfn|Spurgeon|2012}}  The non-exclusive deal was made with Toronto-based [[Kobo Inc.]]{{sfn|Indian Country Today|2012}}

